<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="sl">Repair vs. Replace</p>
    <h2>When to repair a range hood, when to replace it</h2>
    <p class="lead">Range hoods are generally practical to repair rather than replace. Luxury integrated units especially favor repair &mdash; replacement involves cabinetry work.</p>
    <div class="rvr-grid">
      <div class="rvr-card repair">
        <h3>Repair makes sense when:</h3>
        <ul class="rvr-list">
          <li>Fan motor failure on a unit under 10 years old</li>
          <li>Issue is grease-related (often no parts cost)</li>
          <li>Wolf, Miele, or Gaggenau integrated unit &mdash; replacement requires cabinet work</li>
          <li>Controls or lighting only &mdash; inexpensive parts</li>
          <li>Total repair under 50% of replacement value</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="rvr-card replace">
        <h3>Replace makes more sense when:</h3>
        <ul class="rvr-list">
          <li>Budget under-cabinet hood is 10+ years old with motor failure</li>
          <li>Structural damage to the hood body</li>
          <li>Control board cost exceeds 60% of unit replacement value</li>
          <li>Unit is corroded from long-term grease exposure</li>
          <li>Customer wants to upgrade to ducted from ductless anyway</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

